\section*{Tidyverse Overview}
\label{sec:orgb397835}
The tidyverse is a collection of packages developed and advocated for by \href{https://github.com/hadley}{Hadley Wickham}, a statistician who is a prominent R developer who has contributed to many extremely popular packages, including ggplot, roxygen, devtools, shiny, Rcpp, Rmarkdown, and many more. All tidyverse packages share the same core philosophies of improving readability of code, encouraging highly organized data, reusing data structures, and embracing the functional programming nature of R. If you want to read more about the ideas behind the tidyverse, check out \href{https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/tidyverse/vignettes/manifesto.html}{the tidy tools manifesto}.

Think of the tidyverse as a grammar for R. Most of the stuff I'll cover is perfectly possible with base R. However, functions in the tidyverse are designed to make common tasks easier to code and more readable. Learning how to use tidyverse packages will make your code easier to understand at a glance, be it manipulating data frames, strings, or making publication-quality plots (as you all probably know, ggplot is better than the base plotting functions in almost every situation).

The following packages are part of the tidyverse (underlined packages are covered in this post):
